05639nam a22008055i 9780231549332DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018040738  a97802315493327 a10.7312/pric191302doi  a(DE-B1597)526876  a(OCoLC)1076373533  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHT243.J3b.P75 2019 7aLIT0080302bisacsh04a307.7609522231 aPrichard, Franz, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aResidual Futures :bThe Urban Ecologies of Literary and Visual Media of 1960s and 1970s Japan /cFranz Prichard. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b20 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies of the Weatherhead East Asian Institute, Columbia University00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Prelude to the Traffic War Infrastructural Aesthetics of the Cold War -- tChapter Two. Disappearance Topological Visuality in Abe Kōbō’s Urban Literature -- tChapter Three. Landscape Vocabularies For a Language to Come and the Geopolitics of Reading -- tChapter Four. An Illustrated Dictionary of Urban Overflows -- tChapter Five. Photography as Threshold and Pathway After Reversion -- tChapter Six. Residual Futures -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the postwar years, an eruption of urbanization took place across Japan, from its historical central cities to the outer reaches of the archipelago. During the 1960s and 1970s, Japanese literary and visual media took a deep interest in cities and their problems, and what this rapid change meant for the country. In Residual Futures, Franz Prichard offers a pathbreaking analysis of the works wrought from this intensive urbanization, mapping the ways in which Japanese filmmakers, writers, photographers, and other artists came to grips with the entwined ecologies of a drastic transformation.Residual Futures examines crucial works of documentary film, fiction, and photography that interrogated Japan’s urbanization and integration into the U.S.-dominated geopolitical system. Prichard discusses documentary filmmaker Tsuchimoto Noriaki’s portrait of the urban “traffic war” and the remaking of Tokyo for the 1964 Olympics, novelist Abe Kōbō’s depictions of infrastructure and urban sociality, and the radical notions of landscape that emerge from the critical and photographic work of Nakahira Takuma. His careful readings reveal the shifting relationships among urban materialities and subjectivities and the ecological, political, and aesthetic vocabularies of urban change. A novel cultural history of critical urban discourse in Japan, Residual Futures brings an interdisciplinary approach to Japanese literary and visual media studies. It provides a vital new perspective on the infrastructural aesthetics and entangled urban and media conditions of the global Cold War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aMass mediaxSocial aspectszJapan. 0aSocial ecologyzJapanxHistory. 0aUrban ecology (Sociology)zJapan. 0aUrbanizationzJapanxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Japanese.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2019 Englishz97